In addition to var, we now have 2 new identifiers available for storing values â€” let and const. Unlike var, let and const have a block scope
example of var:
var snack = 'Meow Mix';

function getFood(food) {
    if (food) {
        var snack = 'Friskies';
        return snack;
    }
    return snack;
}

getFood(false); // undefined
If change var to let:
let snack = 'Meow Mix';

function getFood(food) {
    if (food) {
        let snack = 'Friskies';
        return snack;
    }
    return snack;
}

getFood(false); // 'Meow Mix'
This change in behavior shows that you need to be careful when refactoring old code that uses var. Simply replacing var with let can lead to unpredictable program behavior.
